ce:section.ce:para:
Hydrogels formed via self-assembly between CDs and LMWGs have garnered considerable interest due to the method's many advantages, such as its low manufacturing cost, broad range of applications, and reversibility [78,79]. The LMWGs encompass a broad spectrum, including, but not limited to, amides, nucleobases, dendrimers, and fatty acids (Fig. 4
                        ). These LMWGs offer the possibility of designing hydrogel characteristics that are to one's liking. Using scintillators, Quaranta et al. reported the production of a thin xerogel layer of carbon-based nanodots [83]. Integrating QDs to organic or hybrid networks allows for the widespread use of their optical properties, from luminescent systems for photovoltaics to optical computers. Since CQDs are resistant to radiation, they could be useful in scintillation devices. This is an exciting idea. Because of their highly delocalized structure, CQDs are able to withstand intense laser light without deteriorating [84]. CQDGs were synthesised by Cayuela et al. utilising an LMWG, and the authors detail the hybrid materials' efficacy as novel, robust, fast, and easy-to-use fluorescence sensors [85]. Gels not only dramatically improve fluorescence, but also have a major impact on selectivity. Surface carboxyl groups on CQDGs showed to be the most selective for detecting Ag+ ions. The addition of CDs not only made the hydrogels more robust, but it also made the CDs brighter. As a next step, composite gels were made using CDs with various surface groups (passivate-CDs with amino groups, thiol-groups, and carboxylic acid groups). Incorporating GQDs, enzymes, and small molecule hydrogelators, Sahub et al. created a composite hydrogel system for sensitive and useful organophosphate sensing [86]. Enzyme-functionalized gel networks were created by incorporating acetylcholinesterase (AChE) and choline oxidase (ChOx) into the self-assembled GQDs/Gel materials during their creation. The hydroperoxide produced by the dynamic enzymatic reaction effectively turned off the fluorescence of the GQDs contained in the hydrogels. GQDs/Enz/Gels fluorescence was restored after being treated with the pesticide dichlorvos. The sensitivity demonstrated by these hybrid hydrogels in the detection of oxy-form organophosphate pesticides bodes well for the anticipated development of quick and ecologically acceptable procedures. It is stated that functionalized carbon nanodots have been incorporated into a new 5-aminosalicylic acid-derived low molecular weight salt hydrogel [87]. The presence of heavy metal ions causes the CDs to react differently photoluminescently in the aqueous environment [88]. The unique hybrid CD-gel nanostructures presented here show promise as highly programmable luminous media, with potential applications in environmental and biomedical heavy metal ion detection. Nanostructures made from non-toxic precursors have the potential to be biocompatible, opening the door to their usage in diagnostics, drug activation, and controlled drug release. Using CQDs as building blocks, sun et al. shown, allowed for the creation of fluorescent vesicles and chiral hydrogels. Electrostatic interaction between the positively charged CQDs and the negatively charged biosurfactant NaDC is used to form the vesicles, eliminating the need for time-consuming synthesis, as well as the use of undesirable chemical solvents, and complex procedures [89]. NaDC concentration was increased while constructing chiral hydrogels with reduced peptide GSH. When CQDs are present in a gel, not only do they make the gels bright, but their mechanical strength is also improved. Intriguingly, the xerogels also exhibit robust emission, which offers a simple technique for creating ready-to-use phosphors that were then evolved into a reliable sensing platform for on-site and speedy sensing of Cu2+. In a different paper, the author used continuous-flow microfluidics to produce hydrogels and hydrogel/QD-hybrid materials based on dipeptides in a continuous fashion. Our microfluidic system's microchannels allowed for the consistent entrapment of inorganic QDs of varying sizes and organic porphyrins in a hydrogel generated via supramolecular assembly from Fmoc-FF [90]. In situ microfluidic channel monitoring revealed a dynamic assembly in which QDs were gradually entrapped, leading to the formation of a hybrid hydrogel with uniform QD entrapment. Thus, the development of dipeptide-based multicomponent hydrogels expands the scope of potential uses for such hybrid gels in fields as diverse as biomedical devices, photodynamic treatment, and continuous bioprinting. The spontaneous supramolecular assembly of a backbone-engineered peptide scaffold was described by Misra et al., and the scaffold has been shown to be useful for immobilising semiconductor QDs (Fig. 5
                        ) and in cell culture [91]. The intriguing property of this peptide scaffold is its ability to effectively gelate aqueous phosphate buffers and aromatic organic solvents. Coassembly of chiral gelators and chiral FeS2 QDs via noncovalent interactions allowed for the effective fabrication of chiral fibrous structures that facilitate chirality transfer [92]. The helical pitch and diameter of the cogels were remarkably under control when illuminated by CPL. Not only does this study show how to precisely produce chiral composite nanosystems, but it also sheds light on how to control the helical chirality of composite nanomaterials.
